**Workflow in Credit Card Approval Project**

## Project Vision   
The main objective of this project is to analyze the relationship between explanatory variables that contribute to credit card approvals and denials, through a tool that determines if someone will be preapproved for a credit card, or not. In the digital age, online banking has become the primary way that Americans handle their finances. Credit cards are the secondly most popular non-cash instrument in the world and provide various benefits. Credit cards provide  secure and reliable means of payment, 58 percent of Americans own a credit card, while 41 percent of those Americans report that they pay a monthly credit card bill (Funk et. al, 2007). According to the Pew Research Center, payment of credit card bills varies by income; for example, families making less than an annual income of 30,000 dollars are less likely to make credit card payments in full. As an overwhelming majority of Americans report they own some type of credit card; it is important for consumers to choose the right card with the right benefits, convenience and short term financing seem to be major contributors in this decision. Furthermore, credit cards serve as a cushion for families with a lower annual income. However, credit cards can accumulate high amounts of debt for customers and can negatively impact an individual’s credit score (Funk et. al, 2007). Thus, it becomes an issue between credit companies and their consumers to determine the right fit for each credit application. Additionally, credit card companies operate as issuers, acquirers, and network operators (Chakravorti, 2003).   
Firstly, it must be understood that credit card consumers are not only individuals, but are also merchants, groups,  and organizations. Together, the individuals that own a credit card make up 22 percent of the costs associated with operating credit card companies (Chakravorti, 2003\). Over time, these costs have increased percentages due to inflation’s impact on rising costs. Due to the increasing costs of maintaining credit cards for consumers, it becomes critical for credit card companies to ensure they do not approve individuals that will accumulate vast amounts of debt and that will become a liability for the credit card company. To combat this, banks have created a credit card preapproval system. These systems work similar to actual credit card approvals, but are instantaneous; however, these systems are not always accurate.   
The creation of our tool, that effectively predicts if someone will be preapproved for a credit card or not, would transform the way credit card companies can ensure security for their company, prospective customers, and current customers. Our tool would eliminate the aspect of inaccuracy that is dealt with in preapproval forms and would allow credit card companies to expand their customer base within  their target audiences. Further, it would stop the process of an individual being preapproved, having a human review their application, and ending up being denied in the final steps; this wastes company time, money, and resources, allowing companies to allocate these things elsewhere.

## Motivation & Project Purpose, Goals  
As credit debt has accrued in the United States, banks and credit companies have needed to discover new ways to limit the amount of debt their own companies are contributing to the national debt total. Fortunately, credit companies know most of their business is managed through credit cards. Many banks have already implemented a preapproval credit form that customers can fill out, but as previously mentioned, it becomes complex and wasteful of time to manually review a new customer’s application if they won’t be approved for a credit card after all. Thus, insinuating a need for a more complex and thorough way of preapproving customers for a credit card. Ultimately, the way credit card companies are currently operating is not optimal and is inefficient for the financial benefit of the individual companies.   
In the creation of our model, we have a roadmap to follow. This roadmap was created based on our goals of collecting data and utilizing automation for work distribution and management, managing privacy agreements and risk management, handling technical debt, and contributing to open source contributor channels and reaching a large audience. Further, we need to conduct research in order to ensure the efficiency and accuracy of the tool, aligning with the main project goals. Questions to consider include: how many credit applications happen per year, how many people utilize the credit card preapproval forms, what primary factors impact approval rates? These key questions are critical to the development of the model, ensuring the model can run without crashing.

## Methodologies & Implementation   
Creating a timeline will help the team stay on track and ensure reliability for prospective companies that are interested in purchasing the tool. Efficiency and optimization are beneficial to the success of the production of the tool to other companies, demonstrating innovation to potential customers. The outline of the formatted timeline continues as follows, form a deliverable, begin work distribution, tool building, release the tool. Forming our deliverable will implement a strong message and displays a forefront of our goals to the public. After this, work distribution begins. Assigning necessary teams to the project to complete is the first step. Further, we need to choose a coding language constructive to the data, this is typically python but can be reevaluated as a whole team. Then gather the data that will be used in the tool (also known as training data), this can include both private and open source data, but it needs to be determined how we can display results if private data is used. Additionally, we must utilize other automation and planning software to ensure organization within the project, platforms like Clickup and monday.com work well. After selecting platforms, managing work assignments, and forming a concrete plan for the project, tool building can begin. During this, the team will focus on meeting deadlines, coding, marketing, and implementing all necessary aspects into the tool. The model will contain various mathematical calculations such as an ROC score, a determinant of how well a model correctly predicts the positive and negative classes, and an AIC score, a score that determines the best model that we’ll use for the tool, and cross validation, a methodology of statistical security technique that is used to selected models in machine learning. Bug fixes should be conducted on the model itself, while team members working on the tool report should begin summarizing its findings. After bug fixes, the tool can be exhibited to the public. This can be done via a conference, or another platform that can reach a large audience besides the internet. Further, the tool should also be announced on Github, an open source platform. On Github, the code for the tool can be shared to promote the findings in our model.

## Open Source   
The multitude of benefits from open source platforms include inclusivity and accessibility. By allowing anyone to view a project’s content and resources, it promotes reliability and convenience to people across the globe. Primarily, any developer or financial manager can access the project and read the goals, vision, and its implementations. This allows different versions of the tool to come out, for different fields. Financial software engineers can take inspiration from the model produced in this project and produce a new tool that can predict things like if someone would be approved for a loan, purchasing online currencies like cryptocurrencies, and other valuable predictions. Documentation has been proven successful throughout the project; to finalize the foundation of the roadmap, we need to document all possible information that may be made public. Without documentation, the project’s success would not be as widespread as it is. A lack of documentation and open source platforms creates a digital divide among users who want to know more, engineers who build models, and financial employees. In turn, this helps with adjusting the scale of another project this may inspire, on a smaller or larger skill; it creates a platform for demonstrating sleek transitions and adjustments in a project; and, facilitates transforming risk management through automation. Further, various credit companies may inquire about purchasing the tool and its potential applications in analyzing more data. For example, credit card companies may want to analyze the position they play in lowering interest rates and if lowering interest rates may benefit their companies, “...consumers may pay annual fees, finance charges if they revolve, and other fees, such as cash-advance and over-the-limit fees. Issuers compete for cardholders on various dimensions…,” (Chakravorti, 2003). To benefit the overall community of financial advisors, financial engineers, and banking staff, machine learning tools as the one created find ways to combine data science and financial information to create an overall more effective way to inquire upon accurate predictions. Machine learning tools have the potential to transform the financial world, and open source platforms allow individuals to inquire how. Predictions in the financial industry majorly benefit credit card companies because of the vast amount of credit card users in the United States and the large financial transactions that occur on lines of credit.

## Continuous Adaptations and Improvements   
Ensuring accuracy in a model is difficult, but when achieved can positively contribute to the predictions for credit card approvals. Accuracy is both a statistical measurement score and a term used to describe the overall effectiveness of a model. The accuracy of the model must maintain high in terms of effectiveness, if there are changes in the explanatory variables or other factors being considered for credit card approvals, there must be adjustments made to the tool created. For example, if there is a change in the amount of income an individual should earn to be approved for a credit card, or the number of dependents correlating to someone’s income changes, the model would need to be reworked to maintain its accuracy. Further than the various planning methods that have already been implemented in the roadwork map, there must be an additional guide to improvements and developments that can take place in the future. Set by the lead in the project, the guide for improvements should contain possible scenarios to account for, and what course of action should be taken. If executed effectively, it provides a concrete foundation for future scenarios that may occur. As mentioned previously, documentation is important to the success of a project, but also must consider the future implications and issues that may arise in a project’s applications. To make accurate predictions, there must be constant improvements that include improving the original source code, bug fixes, optimization in the construction of the project, and challenges to original thoughts towards building the tool. This is a critical part of the project so that people who work on the project in the future will have an easier time handling future implications. Overall, considering future scenarios while managing the workflow of the  project will benefit the total success of the project.
